no-in-operator

Warns on every use of the `in` operator in expressions. The `in` operator is
usually an escape hatch to suppress TypeScript errors or work around incomplete
types. Prefer type guards, discriminated unions, or proper type narrowing.

Source: custom rule for lintcn
Severity: warn (does not block CI)

Like no-type-assertion, this rule surfaces the actual types involved so
developers and AI agents can see what's happening and choose a better approach.

What Gets Flagged

Every binary `in` expression is flagged (for-in loops are NOT affected):

  "foo" in obj        // warns with type of obj
  key in someRecord   // warns with type of someRecord

Special Case: Union Narrowing

When the right-hand operand is a union type and the checked property exists in
some members but not others, the rule produces a special message suggesting to
use a discriminant property instead:

  type Cat = { kind: 'cat'; meow(): void }
  type Dog = { kind: 'dog'; bark(): void }
  declare const animal: Cat | Dog;

  if ('meow' in animal) { ... }
  // ↑ warns: Property `meow` exists in Cat but not in Dog.
  //   Consider using a discriminant property (e.g. `kind`) instead of `in`.

Preferred Alternatives

  // Instead of: 'foo' in x
  // Use discriminated unions:
  if (x.kind === 'cat') { x.meow() }

  // Use type guards:
  function isCat(x: Animal): x is Cat { return x.kind === 'cat' }

  // Use instanceof for classes:
  if (x instanceof Cat) { x.meow() }

What Is NOT Flagged

  for (const key in obj) { }  // for-in loops use different AST node
